jiHere is the testing code for the negative testing scenarios:


@Test
public void testProgramArgsListWithoutValidParams() throws Exception {

    // Create a ParameterTool object with no valid params
    ParameterTool parameters = new ParameterTool();

    // Try to run the main method
    try {
        Main.main(parameters.getRawArgs());
        fail("Should have thrown an exception");
    } catch (Exception e) {
        // Expected exception
    }
}

@Test
public void testProgramArgsListWithValidParamsButInvalidValues() throws Exception {

    // Create a ParameterTool object with valid params but invalid values
    ParameterTool parameters = new ParameterTool("--input=/path/to/file --topic=topic --bootstrap-server=localhost:9092");

    // Try to run the main method
    try {
        Main.main(parameters.getRawArgs());
        fail("Should have thrown an exception");
    } catch (Exception e) {
        // Expected exception
    }
}
Sure, here is the code for the getRawArgs method:


public static String[] getRawArgs() {
  // Get the command line arguments
  String[] args = System.getArgs();

  // Remove the first argument, which is the name of the program
  args = Arrays.copyOfRange(args, 1, args.length);

  return args;
}


I hope this helps